<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Energy efficiency deteriorating in Britain
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S performance in using energy efficiently is showing signs of
deterioration after two decades of almost continual improvement, the
Association of Conservation for Energy has found in an analysis of
government statistics.
The 'energy ratio' - the amount of primary energy needed to produce a unit
of gross domestic product as measured by the Department of Trade and
Industry - declined every year but one between 1970 and 1989. But Mr Andrew
Warren, association director, said: 'Since 1989 there has been a 3.7 per
cent rise in the ratio.'
Ironically it was in 1989 that the government called for a 2 per cent annual
improvement in energy efficiency, against the average of 1 per cent.
</TEXT>
