<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Plans for ID cards attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is considering the introduction of identity cards to help
crack down on social security fraud totalling more than Pounds 1bn a year,
but has come up against strong opposition from civil liberties groups.
Although other European countries such as France and Germany have ID cards,
any discussion of their introduction in the UK has raised Orwellian visions
of the all-seeing, ever-prying state.
However, a recent poll carried out for the Police Federation showed that a
majority of Britons favoured some form of ID card system to help combat
crime.
Responding to weekend reports that Mr John Major, the prime minister,
favoured such a scheme, Liberty, the civil liberties group, said ID cards
could be used to discriminate against some sections of society.
Mr Jeremy Corbyn, a Labour MP on the Commons social security committee, said
that the idea was part of the government's obsession with cutting social
security spending. He added: 'It is another smack of the Big Brother state.'
The Department of Social Security said there were no plans to bring in an ID
card system to help beat fraudsters, although this was being looked at as
one of a range of measures.
The Home Office, whose interests in any ID scheme would cover its impact on
crime, terrorism and immigration, also said nothing was planned immediately.
The DSS is tightening up anti-fraud procedures for payment of benefits.
These include redesigning books for each type of benefit to make these
harder to forge, and encouraging electronic transfer of funds directly into
bank accounts.
The DSS believes the last method, known as automatic credit transfer, is the
most effective against fraud; it is also cheap to administer. But recent
government proposals to highlight this option more clearly on benefit books
raised strong concern about the possible closure of local Post Offices.
</TEXT>
