<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Power companies warned on long-term deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWER COMPANIES have been criticised by the industry's regulator over
attempts to tie customers to long-term contracts in the run-up to market
de-regulation next April.
The Office of Electricity Regulation (Offer) has warned that some of the
contracts may be anti-competitive and has instructed companies to re-draw
them to provide consumers with escape clauses.
The problem has arisen because of the impending introduction of competition
in the power market for medium to large consumers. This has 50,000 users,
ranging from schools to medium-sized business sites, which have to buy from
their local monopoly power distributer.
From April they will be given the right, already enjoyed by the 5,000
largest power consumers, to choose from any electricity company which is
prepared to supply them.
In an effort to keep customers, some regional companies have been offering
discounts for electricity consumed before April to customers who agree to
sign long-term deals lasting up to four years.
In a letter to the companies Offer has ruled that this behaviour takes
advantage of the present monopoly market to preclude other suppliers from
competing effectively after April.
It has told the 12 regional companies in England and Wales and two Scottish
distributers that 'to avoid suggestions of anti-competitive behaviour' it
expects each contract signed before April to include a clause enabling a
customer to be released from the deal after a year. Offer wants contracts
already signed to be amended to reflect this change.
Disclosure of the long-term contracts has prompted concerns about how the
discounts are being financed. Industry regulations prevent regional
electricity companies from cross-subsidising between various parts of their
business.
It is thought that several regional companies have 'over-recovered' in their
monopoly markets this year - they may have charged too much because
inflation estimates have proved incorrect. The regulations require that this
money is not used for discounts in the new competitive market and is
returned to customers in rebates. Offer said: 'Companies must demonstrate to
us that there is no cross-subsidy. Deals should be self-financing.'
Offer has also reminded regional companies that under their licences they
must not discriminate between similar customers when they offer contracts.
It could not say yesterday which of the distributers had been offering
discounts tied to long-term contracts.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
