<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Big drop in wage freezes reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of pay freezes has dropped sharply since the start of the year
and more than two thirds of pay awards remain in the 2 per cent to 4 per
cent band, says the latest pay survey from independent analysts Incomes Data
Services.
The Confederation of British Industry's pay databank continues to report
that nearly a quarter of all manufacturing settlements are freezes. But
according to IDS, of 119 private-sector deals concluded from July onwards,
only five were freezes, 'a much lower number than at the start of the year'.
The apparent decline in freezes and the bottoming out of pay settlements in
the private sector will increase pressure on public-sector managers to offer
employees some sort of pay rise next year in spite of the government's
freeze on public pay bills.
Average pay settlements could also start to shift upwards next month with
the second stage of two-year agreements of 4 per cent at Jaguar, 3.6 per
cent at Rover Group, and 3 per cent at Iveco Ford Trucks following a
six-month deferral.
Some of the higher rises concluded from July include 7.5 per cent (including
bonus payments) for 2,500 employees at Severn Trent Water, and 5.5 per cent
at Calor Gas, which was partly to compensate its 1,800 employees for moving
from a non-contributory pension scheme to a contributory one.
IDS Report 651. IDS, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
