<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Rocard promises to overhaul French Socialist party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michel Rocard yesterday promised an overhaul of France's Socialist party
and launched an attack on the government of Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime
minister, following his election as Socialist leader on Saturday, writes
John Ridding in Paris.
Mr Rocard, former prime minister who has provisionally led the Socialist
party since its crushing defeat in March's general election, won 80 per cent
of the 587 votes cast in a secret ballot for the post of the party's first
secretary. He called for a reorganisation of the party and a rethink of
policies aimed at reviving support.
In his attack on Mr Balladur's centre-right government, Mr Rocard focused on
its conduct of negotiations in the Uruguay Round of Gatt international trade
talks. He said the government had acted irresponsibly and warned that
failure to conclude an agreement with trading partners would have dramatic
consequences.
Mr Rocard also said he was willing to lead a list of Socialist party
candidates in next year's elections for the European parliament. But he only
would do so, he added, if women were given half the places on the list.
Despite Mr Rocard's unopposed victory, however, the divisions within the
party which have contributed to its electoral decline remained in evidence.
More than 100 delegates to the weekend party congress cast blank ballots in
the secret vote and there were 51 abstentions.
The abstentions are believed to have included Mr Roland Dumas, former
foreign minister and an ally of President Francois Mitterrand, who is an
opponent of Mr Rocard.
</TEXT>
