<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Government braced for escalation of strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRENCH government is bracing itself for an escalation of the strikes
surrounding Air France this week, following the failure of weekend
negotiations aimed at defusing the dispute.
The strike by ground staff, protesting against an Air France recovery plan
which includes 4,000 job cuts, is due to be joined tomorrow in a 24-hour
strike by Air France pilots and cabin staff and by unions at Aeroports de
Paris, the airport authority, and at Air Inter, the domestic airline
controlled by Air France.
The dispute, now in its second week, represents a dilemma for the government
of Mr Edouard Balladur, which faces its first serious industrial dispute
since taking office in March and which fears a spread of public-sector
unrest.
The government is seeking to restructure inefficient state-owned industry to
ease pressure on the budget deficit - targeted at FFr317bn (Pounds 36.5bn)
this year - and to enable the sale of state-owned groups it has slated for
privatisation. But such measures threaten to fuel protests within the public
sector and add to widespread anxiety about the unemployment rate, which is
11.7 per cent.
A number of other public sector protests are planned. In addition to the Air
France strike, unions have called for a day of mass action on November 18
which is expected to hit France's railways, postal and telecommunications
services.
France Telecom and the railways are not on the privatisation list, but a
one-day strike earlier this month drew wide support from workers at these
groups, reflecting fears about job cuts and opposition to the government's
employment bill, which is aimed at increasing flexbility in French labour
law.
The threat of broader public-sector actions has prompted the government to
step in quickly at Air France. In negotiations on Friday night and Saturday
morning, Mr Bernard Bosson, the transport minister, offered a series of
concessions to Air France's unions, including a proposal that pay cuts be
limited to 1 per cent for the airline's lowest-paid workers and that
reductions in overtime pay could also be revised.
But the unions rejected the compromise offer and demanded renegotiation of
the recovery plan announced last month by Mr Bernard Attali, Air France's
chairman. 'This dispute cannot be ended unless Mr Attali's plan is
completely redrawn,' a spokesman for the CGT said yesterday.
The government and Mr Attali, however, argue that the plan is vital for the
survival of Air France, which lost FFr3.8bn in the first six months of the
year.
The situation at Paris' main airports was relatively peaceful yesterday
following the clashes between riot police and strikers on Thursday and
Friday. But Air France continued to be severely affected by the dispute,
with only a handful of medium- and long-range flights leaving from Charles
de Gaulle and Orly airports.
Air France said it hoped that tomorrow would see the peak in the dispute and
that negotiations with the unions could be reopened following the planned
24-hour strike by Air Inter and Aeroports de Paris.
The government took some encouragement at the weekend from a pay agreement
with four civil service unions. Under the terms of the agreement, civil
servants will receive a pay rise of 5 per cent for 1994 and 1995, slightly
less than the expected level of inflation.
</TEXT>
