<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Air France chief quits as recovery plan is withdrawn:
Government seeks to preserve 'social peace'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bernard Attali, chairman of Air France, resigned last night after the
French government said it was withdrawing a controversial cost-cutting plan
which triggered a week of strikes at the state-owned airline.
The withdrawal of the plan reflects the government's fear of an escalation
in the dispute and concern that it could prompt wider unrest in public
sector industry. The strike, mainly involving ground staff protesting
against the recovery plan, was due to be joined tomorrow by Air France
pilots and cabin staff and by unions at Aeroports de Paris, the airport
authority, and at Air Inter, the domestic airline controlled by Air France.
The government's decision also raises questions about its ability to push
through the restructuring of state-owned companies which are to be sold as
part of its ambitious privatisation programme. Air France is one of 21
publicly owned groups due to be sold by the centre-right government of Mr
Edouard Balladur.
The government stressed a restructuring plan would still be implemented at
Air France, which suffered losses of FFr3.8bn (Pounds 440m) in the first
half of the year. But it said that amendments must be made to take account
of union grievances.
'Because we must have social peace we must change the plan,' said Mr Bernard
Bosson, the transport minister, said in a statement on French television. He
said that the 4,000 job cuts involved in the original plan could be achieved
without compulsory redundancies and that it was necessary to re-establish
trust with the airline's employees. Mr Bosson gave himself three months to
draw up a new recovery package for the ailing airline.
Mr Attali's continued insistence that his plan was necessary for the
survival of the airline made his position increasingly untenable. His
position was further weakened by the fact that he was an appointee of the
former socialist government, and his future had been in doubt ever since the
centre-right won power at the last election.
Mr Attali, the twin brother of Mr Jacques Attali, who recently resigned as
head of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, said: 'The
public authorities have decided to withdraw the programme to return to
financial equilibrium that I consider indispensable.'
The strike at Air France is the first serious industrial dispute faced by
the French government since it took office in March. Yesterday's climbdown
illustrates the dilemma it faces in its conflicting demands of restructuring
inefficient state-owned companies, many of which it is seeking to privatise,
while trying to avoid social unrest created by an unemployment rate at 11.7
per cent.
A number of other public sector protests were planned before yesterday's
announcements. In addition to the Air France strike, unions have called for
a day of mass action on November 18 which is expected to hit France's
railways, postal and telecommunications services.
The threat of broader public-sector actions prompted the government to step
in quickly at Air France. In weekend negotiations, Mr Bosson had already
offered concessions to Air France's unions, including a proposal that pay
cuts be limited to 1 per cent for the airline's lowest-paid workers and that
reductions in overtime pay could also be revised. Unions representing Air
France ground staff rejected the compromise, demanding that Mr Attali's plan
be abandoned. It was unclear after last night's withdrawal, whether the
unions would now call off the strike.
The original plan, which included the sale of the group's hotel interests
and cuts in overtime pay, was aimed at returning the airline to the black by
the end of 1994.
Attali departs, Page 3
</TEXT>
