<HEADLINE>
FT  23 OCT 93 / Clinton to go to Moscow for summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US president Bill Clinton will travel to Moscow for a summit meeting with
president Boris Yeltsin in mid-January, it was announced yesterday.
Mr Warren Christopher, the US Secretary of State, on a visit to Moscow, said
the summit would take place after the Nato summit meeting in Brussels
scheduled for January 10 and 11, with a tour of eastern Europe by the US
president squeezed in between.
Mr Yeltsin was said to have supported a US plan to expand Nato to include
former Warsaw Pact countries. The plan, which will be discussed by Nato
foreign ministers next month, calls for former east bloc countries to start
with joint military exercises and eventually help with peace-keeping
missions.
Mr Yeltsin characterised these proposals as positive and as deserving
support in principle. It is not clear whether Russia will need pressing to
join Nato itself.
Mr Christopher said he was reassured by the Russian foreign minister Mr
Andrei Kozyrev on fair media coverage in the run-up to parliamentary
elections on December 12. But later Mr Kozyrev refused to even answer a
question on censorship from a correspondent of Pravda newspaper, suspended
by Mr Yeltsin earlier this month.
Mr Christopher said he hoped Congress would lift trade restrictions against
Russia by the end of the year.
President Yeltsin moved yesterday to assert Kremlin authority over Russia's
provinces by changing a draft constitution and ordering new local elections,
Reuter reports from Moscow.
A presidential decree said elections to new-style local parliaments in
Moscow, St Petersburg and more than 60 regions would be held between
December 1993 and March 1994.
But Russia's 20 ethnic republics suffered a serious blow when the
Constitutional assembly drafting a new basic law struck references to their
sovereignty from a new draft.
