<HEADLINE>
FT  23 OCT 93 / Markets: Pause for breath before surging on - Wall Street
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WALL Street paus-ed for breath this week, after a feverish up-ward run, but
by yesterday it seemed to have recovered sufficient confidence to keep the
bull market intact.
The week has been dominated by the third quarter results season, which
produced its usual share of nasty surprises and market jitters.
Yet the main message of the results season so far appears to have been
positive: the gradual recovery of the US economy is intact, with GDP
expanding at around 3 per cent a year, and this has been reflected in the
financial reports from some of the most cyclically sensitive sectors.
Wall Street was particularly pleased on Thursday when Caterpillar, the heavy
equipment company, and Cummins Engine, maker of diesel engines, reported
better than expected results and brisk demand for their machines.
Better results have also been reported by several of the leading US
airlines, with both American Airlines, the largest US carrier, and Northwest
Airlines announcing rare profits for the third quarter.
The market has also took heart from the battle for Paramount Communications,
the film and book company, where QVC Network, the television home shopping
company, has made an an unsolicited Dollars 9.5bn takeover proposal, while
cable company Viacom has made an agreed Dollars 7.6bn offer. Paramount,
while proceeding with the Viacom deal, has been refusing to talk to QVC.
On Thursday, QVC tried to force Paramount to the negotiating table by
turning its bid from a mere proposal, for discussion with the Paramount
board, into a firm offer to its shareholders - a tender offer for 51 per
cent of the company's stock. This offer has the same value as its opening
proposal - Dollars 80 for each Paramount share - but will be all in cash,
rather than a mixture of cash and stock.
Few investors seem likely to accept, since Wall Street is anticipating a
long bidding war for Paramount. But the action could rapidly tease out a
higher offer from Viacom and push Paramount's board to the negotiating
table.
The bid action and encouraging results helped the Dow Jones industrial
average recover yesterday from its week-long weakness and at lunchtime it
stood some 10 points above its all-time closing record of 3,652.1, reached
on August 25.
However, nervousness about long-term US interest rates could prevent it
making much more ground in the near term.
In spite of fears at the start of the week bank lending rates were not about
to tumble, it seemed. However, with demand for loans remaining low and banks
increasingly awash with capital, an erosion of lending margins still looks
likely.
JP Morgan sparked a minor rout by announcing that it was cutting its prime
lending rate - the rate used by banks to determine loans mainly to smaller
businesses and on consumer credit - from 6 per cent to 5.5 per cent. The
news came out of the blue. And its surprise nature added to its shock value
and prompted a 4 per cent drop in bank shares.
Other big commercial banks spent the rest of the week playing down the
significance of the Morgan move, while nervously looking to see who might be
tempted next into a pre-emptive interest rate cut. In one sense they were
right: Morgan, after all, has little business tied to the prime rate, and
the move may be more in undermining competitors than in increasing its own
lending business.
Also, a lower prime may do little immediate damage to bank earnings.
Citibank said a half point cut in its prime rate would cost it Dollars 100m
a year in net interest revenue, although it would probably be offset by
other factors (such as an increase in demand for loans.) Chemical, which
reported third quarter earnings per share of Dollars 1.84 (up from 98 cents
a share) said a prime cut would cost it only around 8 cents a share but it
was not planning to cut, it added.
Market willingness to mark down bank share prices so quickly, though,
reflected the fact that lending margins will have to fall eventually. The
big commercial banks last week reported further advances in their key tier
one capital ratios (even Citibank passed the 6 per cent milestone, a level
almost unthinkable just two years ago) prompting several to question at what
level they would begin to look over-capitalised.
Faced with the choice of dropping their credit standards to attract business
or charging less for loans, most banks would prefer the latter. Bank share
prices may have recouped some of their of their losses by the end of the
week, but the day when all big banks are forced to drop their prime rates
seemed a step closer.
