<HEADLINE>
FT  23 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Falling bond prices undercut
morning rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER a morning rally, US share prices finished at mixed levels yesterday,
as falling bond prices undercut the positive impact of the week's corporate
earnings reports, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 13.14 higher at 3,649.30
after remaining well above the all-time closing high of 3,652.09 until early
afternoon. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 2.08 at
463.28, while the Amex composite was off 0.27 at 477.25. The Nasdaq
composite was ahead 1.41 to 772.69.
At the opening, equities moved decisively into positive territory, as the
bond market registered modest gains over levels reached in Thursday's
sell-off. In reviewing the third-quarter performances of many cyclical
companies, those most affected by business cycles, many investors appeared
to be encouraged by the economic outlook. The perception of improving
conditions was reinforced by Thursday's news that business activity in the
Philadelphia area had surged over the past month.
In the afternoon, however, bonds reversed direction in a nervous reaction to
comments made by Mr Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman. In late
trading, the benchmark 30-year issue was  7/8 lower at 103 23/32 , to yield
5.976 per cent.
Stock prices quickly followed suit, falling back from their earlier highs
with an added drag from program trading. In the last two hours, the market
recovered some steam, but fell short of its initial promise. One of the most
actively traded issues was Caterpillar, up Dollars 4 1/8 to a 52-week high
of Dollars 90 after being upgraded by several analysts on the strength of
its earnings report.
Another advancing cyclical was Cummins Engine, up Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars
87, after it provided forecasters with reasons to expect further profit
gains in the fourth quarter.
Banking issues continued to recover from losses that followed JP Morgan's
cut in its prime lending rate earlier in the week. Bankers Trust climbed
Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 79 3/8 , while Chase Manhattan added Dollars  1/4 to
Dollars 34 1/2 in heavy volume. JP Morgan gained Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 74.
QVC, which has announced an Dollars 80-a-share tender offer as part of a
two-tier deal to acquire Paramount, was down Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 55 on
the Nasdaq. On the NYSE, Paramount was up Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 77 1/2 .
On the Amex, class-A shares in Viacom, Paramount's friendly suitor, fell
Dollars 1 to Dollars 59 3/8 . Its non-voting class-B shares were off Dollars
1 1/8 at Dollars 53 1/2 .
Canada
TORONTO closed mixed in moderate trading. The TSE-300 composite index fell
9.39, or 0.23 per cent, to close at 4,153.81. But advancing issues
outnumbered declines 372 to 358. Volume was 55.54m shares, down from
yesterday's 63.67m shares, and trading value fell to CDollars 642.8m from
CDollars 723.1m.
</TEXT>
