<HEADLINE>
FT  23 OCT 93 / Letters to the Editor: Privatising at BR's convenience
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr WILLIAM HODGSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I write to urge the government to include an element of unbundling in
the forthcoming privatisation of British Rail.
During a recent trip to Turkey, I noticed that the public conveniences in
the main bus station in Ankara serve, I estimate, well in excess of 8,000
clients a day, at a price (effectively index-linked) of almost 8 pence a
visit. This business enjoys a local monopoly, a strong client base, 24-hour
custom all the year round, minimal fixed assets, no working capital
requirements and hence produces an astonishing cashflow.
Could not this element of BR's business be sold separately, under the price
control of, say, Ofbog, thus providing a new utility sector to the FT-SE
index? It is vital that the government obtains the best price for the
potentially profitable parts of what 'silver' is left in the cupboard.
William Hodgson,
Tumblecroft,
Up Marden,
Chichester,
West Sussex PO18 9LA
</TEXT>
