<HEADLINE>
FT  23 OCT 93 / Air France workers clash with police at Orly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STRIKING Air France workers sprayed firehoses (see above), smashed vehicles
and battled with police at Orly, the main domestic airport in Paris,
yesterday, in protest at planned cuts in bonuses and jobs, reports David
Buchan from Paris.
After a morning of violence strike leaders opened talks at the ministry of
transport, but there was no word of what progress had been made, if any.
Aeroports de Paris, which runs Orly and the Charles de Gaulle international
airport, said that by the early afternoon flights were back to normal for
all airlines except Air France, and the runways and roads in and around the
two airports were clear. Continued calm in the industry largely depended on
the outcome of the talks at the transport ministry, officials said.
Earlier some 3,000 strikers had attempted, in their fourth day of industrial
action, to march out on to Orly's runways, but had eventually been stopped
by French police using teargas. The strikers had caused a considerable
amount of damage, Aeroports de Paris said.
Mr Marc Blondel, leader of one of the two striking unions, had sent an
appeal to President Mitterrand to intervene.
