<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Presonal Finance (29): How to make
sure they do it your way - The cost of your funeral / There are sound
reasons for pre-payment. Burial-cost increases have exceeded inflation, and
relatives may be saved further stress when they are already under emotional
strain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE'S OWN funeral is not a subject most people like to dwell on. Planning
and paying for it years in advance could seem a little morbid, but funeral
directors have been working on changing public attitudes, with signs of
success.
Death is inevitable, and everyone expects friends and relatives to mourn
them, but comparatively few people in the UK choose to make arrangements in
advance. This is in contrast to the US, where up to three-quarters of
funerals are pre-paid.
The large undertaking groups are now offering schemes that allow you to
choose the type of funeral you would like  - burial or cremation, church
service or simple crematorium ceremony, one limousine or a whole fleet  -
and pay for it at today's prices.
The money goes into an independently administered trust fund, where it is
invested in a mixture of low-risk index-linked gilts and some equities. When
you eventually die, be it three years or three decades afterwards, the
funeral you have chosen is provided, no matter how much prices have gone up
in the meantime.
One of the main arguments for paying for your funeral now is that, in recent
years, the price of funerals has risen faster than the general inflation
rate. According to a survey by Chosen Heritage, one of the largest sellers
of funeral plans, the average funeral in England and Wales cost Pounds
867.29 in 1990, but Pounds 1,048.24 in 1992. In addition, there are
considerable regional variations in the cost of funerals, but some plans
offer the same price all over the country, which could be a good deal for
people in the south-east and south-west of England.
Companies that offer such plans say the other reason many customers choose
them is to save their relatives the stress of having to organise a funeral
when they are already coping with the emotional strain of a death.
'It's what he would have wanted,' is a phrase often heard on the lips of the
bereaved, explaining their choice of funeral arrangements. But how many
people really know what the dead person would have chosen? With pre-payment
plans, you can leave instructions with the funeral directors for every
detail of the proceedings in advance, even down to which hymns should be
sung, the choice of readings, and the route of the funeral cortege.
As soon as the owner of a pre-payment plan dies, relatives can call a
24-hour number, and the funeral directors take over, organising everything
from the removal of the body from the home or hospital to contacting a
minister for the funeral service. The more expensive plans even place an
obituary notice in a local paper, and provide acknowledgement cards for
senders of flowers.
The market for pre-paid funerals is dominated by a few large operators:
Chosen Heritage, run by Great Southern; the Co-operative Wholesale Society's
Funeral Bond; Co-operative Retail Services also has a funeral bond and
pre-payment certificates; Dignity in Destiny, owned by the Plantsbrook
funeral group; and Golden Charter, which uses small independent funeral
directors. Most of these offer a choice of three or four package deals,
ranging from very simple to more ostentatious, but some can be customised to
individual requirements.
Package prices range from Pounds 825 to Pounds 1,450 with Chosen Heritage,
and from Pounds 784 to Pounds 1,395 with the Co-operative Wholesale Society.
The cost can often be paid in monthly instalments over one to three years,
but that may involve a charge for finance. Such packages will not include
extras such as embalming, headstones, flowers or catering.
Three-quarters of funerals in the UK are cremations, so most pre-payment
plans use this as the basis for costs. Burials are more expensive. If you
choose to be buried, some plans allow you to pay for this in advance, others
contribute a fixed amount and will expect your family to make up the
shortfall at the time.
The plans can be implemented only by funeral directors belonging to the
organisation running the scheme  - most have several hundred branches or
affiliates, so finding one locally should not be a problem. However, if you
move abroad, or to an area in the UK where there is no affiliated funeral
director to hand, most of the plans will return your money.
The alternative to picking a group of funeral directors and paying in
advance is the traditional option of a funeral insurance plan, offered by
many life insurance companies. Many of the companies offer 'guaranteed
acceptance' schemes for people aged over 50 or 55 and under 80, with no
medical needed. Insurance policies of this sort are generally of the
whole-of-life, without-profits type, so there is no cash surrender value,
and the sum assured does not increase. Whether or not it is good value
depends on how soon the policy holder dies.
Most policies are taken out by people over 60, who may well live for another
25 years. By that time inflation will have eroded the value of the sum
assured, and they may have contributed in premiums more than the final sum
paid out.
For example, with the Norwich Union, a 65 year-old man would pay Pounds 19 a
month for a sum assured of Pounds 2,500, while a woman of the same age would
pay Pounds 16.58. For a pair of 75-year-olds, the same level of cover would
cost Pounds 34.55 and Pounds 28.28. If death occurred within two years of
the policy's start, the company would only pay out 1.5 times the premiums
paid, rather than the sum assured.
By comparison, Chosen Heritage's mid-range Traditional plan, spread over two
years, costs Pounds 45 a month for a person of either sex and any age. Once
the full amount (Pounds 1,080) has been paid, provision of a funeral at the
required standard is guaranteed. If the funeral service is needed before all
of the instalments have been paid, the guaranteed price still applies, but
the balance due must be paid by the family.
The main advantage of insurance over pre-payment is flexibility in the
choice of funeral directors: the money is not tied in any way. However, the
full burden of planning the funeral does fall on the family with this
system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
