<DATE>931022
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (24): Safety in
numbers? Not always - Rationalisation / A reduction in the multitude of
funds could benefit investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO THE casual observer, there would seem to be too many unit trusts. At the
end of August, 1,537 funds were available from 160 management companies,
giving the first-time investor a bewildering choice.
Every year, the number of funds on offer seems to increase remorselessly. In
the bull market of 1987, there were just 1,137 funds from 139 companies on
offer. Even allowing for a slight expansion of the definition of a fund in
June 1993 (following the Unit Trust Association's redesignation as the
Association of Unit Trusts and Investment funds), this represents a
substantial advance.
It is not as if fund management companies were making much money out of all
this diversity. Take the example of the international equity growth sector,
where the investor had 158 funds to choose from at the start of September.
Just over a third of those funds (54) had less than Pounds 10m under
management. Not only is it hard to offer a truly international spread with
that kind of sum, it is also hard to see how the manager can be making a
profit. Even on a 1.5 per cent annual charge, a Pounds 10m trust would bring
in just Pounds 150,000 of revenue a year. By the time you have paid the
manager, and allowed for the costs of running the fund, you will be left
with loose change.
Consumers could certainly have a more than adequate choice with a much
smaller range of funds; every sector could have its index fund, a selection
of 'value' or recovery managers, growth stock players and small-company
specialists. Add in a few funds with different charging structures (some
with low front-end charges and exit fees, others with high initial charges
and a low annual fee), and you could probably get by with 20-25 funds in
each sector.
Despite the apparent need for the industry to rationalise, there is little
sign of change. The problem is that history has shown that it is much easier
to raise money by launching a new fund than it is to generate interest in an
existing trust. 'It is much easier to get press coverage for new funds,'
says Judy Delaforce, product development manager at fund management group
Fidelity. Peter Emms, group marketing director at M&amp;G, says that new funds
give intermediaries a chance to arouse the interest of their clients.
There have also been good reasons to launch many recent funds, argues
Delaforce. 'With the recession, it has been appropriate for some more
cautious funds to be launched, such as money market trusts, balanced funds
(those which include both bonds and equities) and controlled-risk funds
(those which use futures and options),' she says.
But investors face the problem of choosing a fund that turns out to be last
year's fashion. If the fund shrinks, as investors move on to the latest fad,
it becomes difficult for the manager to produce a strong performance,
because he is forever having to sell investments to meet redemptions.
Furthermore, fund management groups have a natural incentive to put their
best managers in charge of their largest funds, so investors in a small fund
can lose out.
So what scope is there for an industry shake-up? Some managers may be happy
to carry on as they are. 'Many of the small trusts are managed by
private-client stockbrokers and portfolio managers who have set them up for
their own clients,' says Delaforce. 'Brokers find it more profitable to run
their own unit trusts than to sell someone else's'
For the moment, most groups in the unit trust industry are enjoying the good
times, as funds flow in at the rate of around Pounds 1bn a month. The
pressure to rationalise, which must have been intense in a bear market like
that of 1990, has eased.
But some companies have given up the ghost, as when insurance group Aetna
sold its trust range to Thornton fund managers. The most substantial recent
reorganisation occurred when Henderson merged with Touche Remnant. The
combined group quickly produced plans to streamline its trust range from 35
to a more manageable 21.
Although mergers require the approval of unitholders, there is normally no
reason for them to object. Most mergers are conducted on an offer-to-offer
basis, to leave a unitholder no worse off. If fund A, with an offer price of
100p, merged with fund B, with an offer price at 50p, then a unitholder with
1,000 units in fund A would find himself with 2,000 units in fund B.
However, there is a potential cost from government stamp duty, which is
deemed to be payable when trusts merge. This can discourage some managers
from rationalising their ranges.
What will probably halt the flow of fund launches is if managers achieve
success in selling the trusts that they have already. There are some signs
of this happening. 'Promoting your existing funds is becoming more
acceptable to clients, if you can show them a solid performance,' says
Fidelity's Delaforce, who in September launched a marketing campaign based
on the group's European fund.
M&amp;G has long used advertising campaigns which emphasise the success of some
of its long-running funds, such as the Recovery unit trust. It is currently
relaunching an old campaign  - 'The only three funds you'll ever need'  -
based on its Recovery, Managed and European Dividend funds.
A large fund can afford to spend more on marketing and attract more
investors. It will be perceived as a less risky choice, on the 'no-one ever
got fired for buying IBM' principle. It can also, once the annual management
fee has grown sufficiently, afford to attract investors by cutting the
initial charge. So by the year 2000, the industry may yet be leaner, more
efficient animal than it is now.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
