<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (23): More popular
now inflation is down - Bond and cash funds / There's a prospect of capital
growth, income or both. But high yields may eat up capital, so investors
should know what they are buying
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIT TRUSTS in the UK have been dominated by equities, with bond and cash
unit trusts accounting only for a small proportion of the industry. The
reverse is true in the US, where the mutual fund industry is weighted in
favour of bond and money market funds.
The reasons for this are largely historical. 'The UK unit trust industry was
started with an equity fund,' explained Victoria Nye, of the Association of
Unit Trusts and Investment Funds (AUTIF). 'The public in the UK has been
able to find low-risk savings at the building society, and could in any case
buy gilts directly.'
The advantage of buying gilts  - UK government bonds  - directly is that the
charges are lower than for unit trusts. The commission on a gilt purchase
bought through the Post Office is Pounds 1 for the first Pounds 250, then
50p for every extra Pounds 125 or part. Those who buy large amounts through
a stockbroker are also likely to pay less than for a unit trust, where the
usual charges are a 5 per cent initial fee and a 1 per cent annual
management charge.
There is also a tax disadvantage to buying gilts in a fund. Gains are liable
to capital gains tax, whereas gilts bought directly are CGT-exempt. The
AUTIF is lobbying to end this discrimination and, in its Budget submission
this year, has called for gilt funds to be made exempt from CGT.
It has also succeeded in securing a change which will make UK-based bond
funds more attractive to non-UK taxpayers. UK-based unit trusts do not pay
income gross but, from the start of the 1994 tax year, they will be able to
do so to non-UK taxpayers.
For those who do not have the time or the expertise to manage a portfolio of
gilts or other bonds, bond funds offer to take the hassle out of tricky
investment decisions. They have been increasing in popularity during a rally
in bond prices in the UK, thanks to low inflation and low short-term
interest rates. Net sales of UK and international fixed-interest funds
totalled Pounds 332.4m in the first half of the year, compared with Pounds
95.3m in the first half of 1992.
The trigger for the rally in the UK was sterling's departure from the
exchange rate mechanism, which led to a spate of interest rate cuts and to a
rise in bond prices. Interest rates have also started to fall in Europe,
again leading to capital gains for those holding international bond funds.
With UK base rates at 6 per cent, long-term gilts now yield more than cash,
a factor which has not been overlooked by income-seeking investors. Analysts
such as BZW do not expect the difference in returns between equities and
bonds to be as great in the 1990s as in the 1980s, and expectations are that
inflation will be lower in the 1990s  - factors which are favourable to the
sale of bonds.
Bond funds offer investors income, capital growth, or a combination of the
two. Some offer a high yield, which is achieved purely by eating up capital.
That might be attractive to some investors, but they should know what they
are buying. There are three main types of fixed-interest fund: UK gilt and
fixed interest, international fixed interest and offshore bond funds.
UK gilt and fixed interest funds: Most of these are dominated by gilts, but
some also invest in the fixed-interest shares of companies. Since a company
is more likely to go bust than the government, the increased risk is often
reflected by a higher yield.
The top two performers in the three years to September 1, according to
Micropal, were: Abtrust Fixed Interest (84 per cent growth with net income
reinvested; current yield 7.1 per cent) and Aetna Preference (69 per cent;
7.7 per cent). These invest heavily in preference shares, which pay a fixed
dividend and rank ahead of ordinary shares in terms of dividend payment and
capital repayment in the event of a wind-up.
International bond funds: These are not confined to investing in UK-issued
fixed-interest bonds, but also deal in those issued by foreign governments
and corporations. They are considered to be riskier than UK bond funds,
because of the added currency factor.
European bonds are currently regarded as attractive, because interest rates,
which are higher on the Continent than in the UK, have begun to fall, and
this should lead to capital gains. Managers of a high-income fund are likely
to be heavily invested in the high-yielding bond markets such as Italy and
Spain.
The highest performing funds in the one year to September 1, according to
Micropal, were: Guinness Flight Global High Income bond (44 per cent growth
with net income reinvested; 7.6 per cent yield) and Invesco International
bond (38 per cent; 5.5 per cent).
Offshore bond funds: Their main advantage to UK investors, particularly
non-taxpayers, is that income is paid gross. A UK-resident non-taxpayer does
not need to reclaim tax from the Inland Revenue, which is what they would
have to do if they invested in an onshore bond fund.
Even resident UK citizens who are liable for tax may find offshore bond
funds attractive, because the tax payment can be delayed. Investors worried
about risk should look for offshore bond funds which are recognised by the
Securities and Investments Board  - the chief regulator for the financial
services industry in the UK.
Performance figures for offshore funds are usually quoted on an
offer-to-offer basis. This is because some funds have a single price but add
on an initial charge, so if all funds were ranked on an offer-to-bid basis,
the single-priced funds would receive an unfair advantage. However, the
effect of quoting in this way is that the performance figures are better
than the returns which would actually have been achieved by an investor.
The highest performing sterling fixed-interest offshore bond funds in the
three years to September 1, according to Hardwick Stafford Wright, were:
Hypo F&amp;C RA Sterling bonds (72 per cent growth, no yield and Barclays
Sterling bond (72 per cent growth; 8.5 per cent yield).
Cash unit trusts: Unlike the bond funds, these do not invest in
fixed-interest securities but in the money markets, where money is bought
and sold for short periods by institutions and rates change daily. Yields
are quoted net of charges.
The main advantage is that a higher rate is paid on a lower minimum than can
easily be found at bank or building societies. Speed of access is similar to
a postal account.
The fund with the highest return in the year to September 1, according to
Micropal, was LAS Maximum Distribution, with growth of 5.85 per cent. The
second best trust - Lazard Money Market  - grew by 5.84 per cent.
</TEXT>
