<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): Still
vulnerable to political upheaval - Investing in the Far East / The best
route is through a collective fund. But be wary, and seek growth rather than
income
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARGUMENTS for investing in the Far East appear to be very clear to UK
investors, judging by the reception given to regional funds launched this
year.
The economies of Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, South Korea, Taiwan,
Thailand, Indonesia and the Phillipines are among the most dynamic in the
world. The marketing brochures spell it out with charts that show growth
rates in the region to be at least two or three times higher than in Europe
or the US, and forecast that they will continue that way. They speak of the
entrepreneurial spirit of the people, and how they are at the vanguard of
new technology, while keeping wages low.
Healthy economic growth is usually accompanied by equally health stock
market growth, and this has been the case in most of South East Asia. Stock
markets in the region have been buoyant this year  - several, including
Singapore, the Phillipines and Hong Kong, have been hitting all-time highs.
Funds investing in the Far East have been among the best performing in
recent years. If five years ago, on a hunch, you had put Pounds 1,000 into
the Gartmore Hong Kong unit trust, it would have grown to Pounds 3,332 by
now.
However, if, after hearing those arguments, you start to wonder why anyone
would want to invest in boring old developed countries, it may be time to
point out some of the downside. It is well known that high rewards do not
come without some level of risk  - and there are plenty of risks associated
with investing in the Far East.
For a start, there are the repercussions of political upheaval. When Chinese
troops went in to put down the student protest in Tiananmen square in 1989,
the Hong Kong stock market plummeted, as did several others in the region.
They rebounded in time, but Chinese political events and rumours can still
make the Hong Hong market jittery, and that is unlikely to change before
1997, when it reverts to Chinese rule. China is not the only problem; the
Phillipines still suffers political instability, there are occasional coups
in Thailand, and so on.
Because many of these economies are export-led, there is a knock-on effect
when the west goes into recession. The home markets are also developing very
fast, but they cannot always take up the slack when overseas sales fall off.
The currency exposure involved in investing in the area is also a risk - the
strong yen has contributed to the good performance of many Japanese funds,
but it can work the other way. For example, inflation in China, currently
running well into double digits, could force a devaluation of the renminbi,
which means that assets held in the Chinese currency would lose value for
foreign investors. Foreign investors can also face complications due to
currency exchange controls.
Another feature of even some relatively developed markets in the region is
that accountancy standards, information disclosure and insider trading
legislation are not quite what UK fund managers are used to. There are also
structural constraints on foreign investment in some countries. For example,
Korea allows a maximum of 10 per cent of any one company's stock to be held
by foreign investors, and Taiwan has similar rules. Sometimes there are ways
around this, for example locally registered funds can buy the stock, and
their shares are then bought by foreigners, but this can add to costs.
If you are looking for income, you would not be well advised to look East  -
dividends from south-east Asian markets are low or non-existent. Rather,
this is the place to put some of your money if you are not likely to need it
for a good few years. Managers of funds concentrating on the smaller markets
in the region tend to take a long-term view, and it is sensible for
investors to do the same. Short-term gains are possible, but not guaranteed,
as the markets can be volatile; however, the prospects for fundamental
economic growth are indisputable. If you ride the dragons and tigers for
long enough (and are not put off by the occasional tumble), you should come
out with substantial capital gains.
For the average UK investor attracted by the idea of devoting a corner of
the portfolio to the Far East, the easiest way is through a UK authorised
unit trust or investment trust. It is possible to buy shares in some
companies directly, but this is not a commonly-used option for private UK
investors.
UK authorised unit trusts are limited by law as to what proportion of their
funds they can invest in unrecognised stockmarkets  - this can be a
disadvantage for China funds, for example, as neither of the mainland
Chinese exchanges are recognised. There is also the risk of becoming trapped
in illiquid markets when investors start cashing in units.
Investment trusts are closed-end funds, ie investors buy and sell shares on
the open market rather than selling them back to the manager. This means
that the manager has more freedom to invest for the long term, without
worrying about whether enough of the portfolio is in very liquid stocks
which can easily be cashed in if investors panic and withdraw their money.
Charges are lower on investment trusts than unit trusts, but investors also
have to cope with fluctuating discounts to net asset value. Also, if a trust
falls very heavily out of favour, you may have difficulty finding a buyer.
As at September 1, there were 89 Japanese unit trusts, 46 in the Far East
including Japan, 62 in the Far East excluding Japan, and five in
Australasia. The funds had a combined total of Pounds 10bn under management.
The investment trust industry is slightly less prolific: there were 30 funds
covering the region, with a combined market capitalisation of Pounds 3.2bn.
Six funds invest in the whole of the Far East including Japan, eight exclude
Japan; seven invest in Japan alone; and nine invest in other single
countries in the region.
The current popularity of the area can be seen from the number of specialist
unit and investment trusts launched recently. This year's crop includes the
Fleming Chinese Investment Trust, the S&amp;P Asian Smaller Companies fund,
Rothschild's Five Arrows Asia Fund, HTR Japanese Smaller Companies, Dunedin
Japan Investment Trust, the Perpetual Japanese Investment Trust, the Govett
Greater China Fund and Jupiter Tyndall's China fund.
As the Japanese economy has matured, it has lost its dragon-like
characteristics, and is now settling down to more western-style growth rates
of 2 or 3 per cent, or even negative growth at times. Japan has regained
favour this year, as the strong yen has combined with a stock market
recovery from last year's low point of just over 14,000 to more than 20,000,
although the economy is still stagnating. However, anybody who put money
into Japan at the height of the stockmarket boom, when the index hit 38,000,
may feel less positive about the current state of the market.
China has been this year's favourite with many UK fund managers, despite
worries over whether its economy has been overheating out of control. Money
has been pouring into all the East Asian stockmarkets on the back of the
Chinese investment boom. Fund managers see the folly of trying to invest
large quantities of money in the miniscule mainland Chinese exchanges at
Shanghai and Shenzhen, so they have been scouring the lists of companies on
nearby exchanges  - particularly Hong Kong, Korea, Taiwan  - looking for
'China plays'. The idea of precisely which stocks can be defined as a China
play varies from manager to manager.
Some have strict criteria: the company must derive a minimum of its profit
or turnover from China. Others take a more relaxed view, regarding almost
any stock on those exchanges as a China play, on the grounds that market
sentiment responds to events in China, and the economies of those countries
are becoming increasingly dependent on doing business with China.
The choice between single-country and more general funds investing in the
whole region is essentially one of risk levels. The former are far more
speculative  - they can do very well one year, but the next they could also
be found floating around the bottom of the performance tables, as there is
little fund managers can do if the market in their chosen country crashes.
Regional funds have the freedom to pull out of markets when they scent
trouble, and so can avoid the depths, but it is also difficult for them to
take full advantage of spectacular growth in individual markets, because
their funds can only put a minority of their money into any single country.
