<DOCNO>FT934-13135</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DJVCQAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931022
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (6): Before looking
round, check what your company has to offer - Going early, The health factor
/ The cost of retaining the protection of private medical care, just when
you may need it most, is high, and the choice of schemes is bewildering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE MEDICAL insurance is part of many remuneration packages. But if you
have never needed to use it, it may be easy to overlook its value by the
time you are offered early retirement.
However, this is likely to happen at just the age when premiums start to
rise steeply and you are increasingly likely to need to make a claim.
Adjusting to the changed lifestyle of retirement can be stressful  - some
newly retired people find their health collapses in the first few months.
So how can you ensure that you do not lose the protection of private health
care just when you may need it most?
When you are negotiating your leaving package, avoid being so taken up with
cash sums that you forget the fringe benefits. The annual premium for
comprehensive private medical cover can be up to Pounds 1,000 for a
55-year-old, and Pounds 1,500 or more for a 65-year-old  - quite a chunk out
of your pension if you have to find the money yourself. If your spouse also
needs to be covered, premiums will be even higher.
One bright spot is that private medical insurance premiums attract tax
relief for UK residents aged over 60, though, to be eligible for this, the
policy may need to be adapted  - for example, any cash benefits for stays in
NHS hospitals are ruled out.
When faced with early retirement, the first thing to do is check what your
company can offer by way of continuing the medical cover that you have
received during employment. Most employers should be able to continue cover
until the annual renewal date for the corporate policy, giving you several
months to look around for an alternative.
Some companies will continue to provide health cover for pensioners in the
group scheme, and pay for it throughout retirement, though this is an
expensive option which only a few employers still offer. Changes to
accounting standards will soon mean that companies have to allow for future
health costs for pensioners on their balance sheets, which may make them
more reluctant to extend cover.
Other companies include pensioners in the company scheme, but only if they
pay their own contributions. This can work out cheaper than arranging cover
individually.
The big advantage to staying with a company scheme is that the older you
get, the more likely you are to have existing medical problems. If you join
a new scheme, most insurers will exclude existing conditions, while one or
two will cover some existing conditions but premiums will rise. Staying with
the same insurer means that any problems will still be covered, at no extra
cost  - this may be the only feasible option if you have made many claims in
the past.
A third possibility is that employers may have negotiated special terms with
their insurer for former employees, but you have to arrange an individual
policy. Check whether cover is treated as continuous, or you are treated as
a new applicant and underwritten from scratch. If you have had any health
problems, this could make it expensive.
Company-arranged schemes can be good deals if you don't want the effort of
shopping around, and the type of cover is what you want. However, if you
suspect the premiums are higher than for comparative policies, or you think
you would be happy with a more basic (and cheaper) level of cover, this
could be the time to start looking elsewhere.
If you have a husband or wife still at work, check whether it would be
possible to get health cover through their employer. If the scheme is
non-contributory, this would obviously be worthwhile. However, if your
partner is also due to retire soon, you could just be postponing the
problem.
Going into retirement, you may be more interested in the peace-of-mind
aspects of private medical insurance than the luxury hospital rooms and fine
food offered by top-of-the-range policies. If you are mainly worried about
long NHS waiting lists for non-urgent surgery, such as hip-replacement
operations, you may be interested in the many low-cost healthcare policies
on the market.
However, low-cost policies come in many different guises. The two principal
devices for reducing costs are cash limits: ie medical expenses are only
covered up to Pounds 15,000 or a similar figure every year, or by limiting
private treatment to cases when you would have to wait for more than six
weeks for treatment under the NHS.
Jan Lawson, of specialist advisers Private Health Partnership, says that
both systems have their drawbacks. If there is a cash limit, it can be
worrying to think that funds may run out half-way through your treatment
should it be more complicated than expected, or that some major surgical
procedures may not be covered.
The six-week rule should mean that you will always get treatment within six
weeks, whether on the NHS or privately. However, the six-week wait is
usually counted from the day that a consultant says you need the operation.
You may have to wait months, or even more than a year, for a consultant's
appointment for some specialities in the NHS. If you opt for a six-week-rule
policy, you may have to be prepared to pay for a private consultation
yourself, or be faced with a long initial wait.
Before you sign up for any policy, make sure you know that what is really
necessary is covered, and don't be distracted by extras which aren't really
necessary but make a policy look more comprehensive than it is.
Jan Lawson gives a final word of warning: if you are choosing a new policy,
don't just base your decision on the premiums for your age now. Look at the
premium table for people five or 10 years older than yourself. Premiums can
rise very steeply after the age of 60 with some insurers, almost doubling by
the age of 65, so the best buy now may not be a good deal at all in a few
years' time. You could be better off going for a slightly more expensive
option now, with premiums which rise much more gradually.
