<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (2): Can you afford
to retire? - Low interest rates have introduced a new hazard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF WORK was such a wonderful thing, someone once said, the rich would keep
it to themselves. Many people are only too eager to give up their daily
stint at the office. A Norwich Union survey found, for example, that two out
of three workers want to retire before they are 60, writes Philip Coggan,
Personal Finance Editor.
Early retirement brings its financial headaches, however. Someone retiring
at 55 could easily live for another 35 years  - longer than the time they
had been in work.
They could find that they spend more, not less, after retirement; after all,
being at work stops you spending money. According to Norwich Union, four in
five people expect to spend more on holidays once they retire. Three
quarters expect to move to more comfortable surroundings.
With a greying population, the state is not likely to be able to afford very
generous retirement benefits: most people expect the government to opt for
an equalised pension age of 65 for men and women. Furthermore, the number of
people who work all their lives at one company, and retire on two-thirds of
their final salary, is extremely limited; Laurentian Financial Group puts it
at 1 per cent. In any case, final-salary schemes, where the employer bears
all the risk, are gradually giving way to money-purchase schemes, where the
eventual pension depends on the investment performance of the fund.
In short, those who want to retire early may need to depend on their own
savings efforts. But how many realise this? Laurentian found that 35 per
cent of workers (including 31 per cent of those over 55) had no idea what
their pension would be.
Even those who have been assiduously saving over the years may have a false
idea of the amount of income they can earn on their capital. Too many people
have a mental '10 per cent' rule, and expect that kind of return on their
money. But earning 10 per cent these days probably requires you to eat into
your capital.
Now that base rates have dropped, and we appear to be in an era of low
growth and low inflation, 5 per cent net may be the best that savers can
expect to earn without eroding their capital. In other words, for every
pound of income you expect to earn from your savings in retirement, you need
to have 20 in capital. To earn Pounds 10,000 a year from savings, you must
build up a capital sum of Pounds 200,000.
Those who have built up adequate provision through a personal pension may
still find the timing of early retirement a bit of a gamble. Most of the
pension fund must be used to buy an annuity, which will provide income for
the rest of the individual's life. Annuity rates are set with reference to
yields on long-term gilts; if you lock in while yields are low, your income
suffers. And if you die one day after buying the annuity, the capital could
be lost.
These drawbacks have led to the concept of staggered vesting, the pensions
buzzword of the moment. It allows receipt of pension benefits to be phased
over several years. But staggered vesting is not a cure-all and, as Eric
Short explains below, its suitability depends on circumstances.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
