<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (3): Check what you
lose for years not worked - Going early, The pension choice / And before
taking a cash sum, consider carefully whether your reduced pension will be
adequate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS MORE employees, particularly men, stop work early, either voluntarily or
through redundancy, they inevitably wonder whether their pension will be
adequate.
The early-retirement benefits available from occupational schemes are set
out in the trust deed and rules. In final-salary schemes, the
early-retirement pension is usually based on a formula which takes account
of the number of years' service to retirement and the employee's earnings at
or near retirement, less a reduction which is related to the number of years
between the early and normal retirement dates.
The reduction may be made on an actuarial basis, to allow for the pension's
being taken early and for a longer period on average, and because fewer
contributions will have been paid and fewer years will have been available
to build up the fund.
The reduction could be as high as 6 per cent in respect of each year  - a 30
per cent reduction for an employee with a normal retirement age of 65 but
who retires at 60.
Many schemes make a less severe reduction  - 3 or 4 per cent for each year
year  - even though this means that each early retirement will cost the
scheme a substantial amount of money. Some may even make nil or nominal
reductions for retirement taken within two or three years of normal
retirement, usually to encourage early departure.
But, as a typical example, an employee in a scheme that provides a pension
of 1/60th of final earnings for each year of service, and who would attain
30 years' service by age 65, would receive a pension of half (30/60ths) his
final earnings at 65. But if he takes early retirement at 60, then his
pension would be 25/60ths of his earnings at 60, less a reduction which
could vary between 5 per cent and 30 per cent of the pension.
If employees take early retirement as a result of being made redundant, then
many schemes provide more favourable benefits through lower reductions and
the crediting of additional years of service.
Employees have the option to convert part of their pension to a tax-free
cash sum, up to the limits set by the Inland Revenue. The benefit statement,
available on request for early retirement, would set out the alternatives of
a full pension or a cash sum plus reduced pension.
Employees need to consider carefully whether the reduced pension will be
adequate before they take the cash sum; or, if they do take it, they must be
prepared to invest the money to boost their income.
Remember that there are no provisions for state pensions to be paid on early
retirement before the state pension age, though employees taking early
retirement may no longer need to pay National Insurance contributions.
This has financial implications for those who take early retirement under
schemes which integrate their benefits with state pensions  - that is, the
pension is based on earnings less a deduction in recognition of the fact
that they will also receive a state pension.
Consequently employees in schemes with integrated benefits, and who retire
before reaching state pension age, face a pension shortfall until they do
reach that age and receive the state pension. This shortfall is more likely
to affect men, who have to wait until they are 65 to receive their state
pension, than women who receive it at 60.
However, many schemes now provide an additional 'bridging' pension,
generally based on the single person's state pension, for employees affected
by this shortfall, until the state pension becomes payable.
Bridging pensions are usually paid only if retirement is taken on or after
the employee reaches 60. Therefore women in these schemes do not receive a
bridging pension  - a fact which has led to complaints about discrimination.
However, the Advocate General's opinion, on a case before the European Court
of Justice, is that schemes could pay bridging pensions to men and not
women, because the combined pensions would be equivalent.
If an employee is taking early retirement because of ill health, then the
benefits, set out in the trust deed, are likely to be more favourable than
normal early retirement benefits.
Meanwhile, employees who take early retirement do have an alternative course
of action. They can opt for a deferred pension (the benefit available when
an employee leaves the scheme), and, if there is more than a year to normal
pension age, take a transfer value to another, personal pension,
arrangement. Some schemes may be willing to pay a transfer value during the
year before normal retirement.
There is no normal pension age with personal pensions. The benefits can be
taken at any time between the 50th and 75th birthdays (both inclusive), and
between the 60th and 75th birthday on retirement annuity contracts. However,
the earlier that benefits are taken, the smaller will be the cash sum and
the lower the annuity rates (which are related to age) at which a pension is
bought.
Individuals taking the benefits have to decide what type of annuity to buy:
level; increasing; on the individual's own life, or with a spouses's
benefit?
Provision of a spouse's benefit or an increasing annuity means that the
annuitant must accept a starting value lower than that provided by a
single-life level annuity. He must compromise between the initial payment
from the annuity, the level of future increases and provision of a spouse's
pension.
However, an alternative approach is available: it is known as 'staggered
vesting', or a phased annuity. The individual uses the flexibility of
cash-in on personal pensions and the facility to take tax-free cash sums.
He decides on the level of net income that he will require in the first
year, then cashes in enough of the personal pension to ensure that some of
the tax-free cash, together with the after-tax value of an annuity purchased
with the balance, provides that income. In this way, the tax-free cash sum
provides part of the income requirements.
This process is repeated each year, with the income from an increasing
number of annuities, plus the tax-free cash sum and the new annuity,
providing the target income.
If investment conditions and annuity rates have been favourable, by the time
the individual reaches 75 and has to cash in what is left in the personal
pension, there should be sufficient value to provide a substantial cash sum
and annuity.
However, staggered vesting needs to be operated on an individual basis each
year, with financial advisers taking a fresh look at clients' requirements,
rather than used as a package, which is the present method of marketing the
concept.
Employees who take early retirement from an occupational scheme can make use
of staggered vesting by taking the transfer option and investing in a
personal pension. The protected-rights element of the personal pension will
have to be taken at normal pension age. But the individual can apply
staggered vesting to the remainder.
</TEXT>
